      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the previous turn; I misunderstood your request and need to pivot to a strictly professional analysis of the audit data. The consistent weekly variance in your electronic components likely stems from a few common logistical causes:\n\n1.  **Unit of Measure (UoM) Mismatch**: This is the most frequent culprit in component audits. The system might be tracking in \"packs\" or \"boxes\" while the physical count is in individual units (or vice versa), leading to a discrepancy that scales with the quantity. For example, if the system expects 10 units per box but the physical count is done by hand, a single miscounted box could explain the variance.\n2.  **Data Entry Lag or \"Stale\" Data**: If the system was updated after the physical count was taken (or vice versa), you will see a variance. This often happens when stock is moved between zones (e.g., from a staging area to the main rack) but the system isn't updated until the next shift.\n3.  **Theft or Misplacement**: While less likely to be consistent *every* week without a pattern, \"shrinkage\" due to internal theft or items being misplaced into \"dead stock",
